ered sacrifices on behalf of the Roman people, and prayed for the community's well-being. As they carried out their ritual obligations, they were assisted by female cult personnel, many of them slave women. DiLuzio explores the central role of the Vestal Virgins and shows that they occupied just one type of priestly office open to women. Some priestesses, including the flaminica Dialis, the regina sacrorum, and the wives of the curial priests, served as part of priestly couples. Others, such as the priestesses of Ceres and Fortuna Muliebris, were largely autonomous.A Place at the Altar offers a fresh understanding of how the women of ancient Rome played a leading role in public cult.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aWomen priestszRome. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh  aBona Dea.  aDecember rites.  aFordicidia.  aFortuna Muliebris.  aJupiter.  aMagna Mater.  aOctober House.  aRoman politics.  aRoman priesthood.  aRoman religion.  aRoman ritual system.  aRoman society.  aRoman women.  aSalian Virgins.  aVesta.  aVestal Virgins.  aVestal costume.  aVestal priesthood.  aVestal regalia.  aVestal virgins.  aVestals.  aancient Rome.  aauthority.  abirth families.  acollegium pontificum.  acultic assistants.  afemale sacrificial incapacity.  afeminine virtue.  afertility.  aflamen Martialis.  aflamen.  aflamines.  aflaminica Dialis.  aflaminica Martialis.  aflaminicae.  afood supply.  afreedwomen.  agender constructions.  ainternal autonomy.  alaywomen.  aleadership.  amale authority.  amola salsa.  amoral probity.  apalla.  apax deorum.  apontifex.  apontifical college.  apriest.  apriestess.  apriestesses.  apriestly couples.  apriestly service.  apublic careers.  apublic cult.  apublic cults.  apublic prie